7. The hidden variable: tempo

Many frame battles are won before meaning is even evaluated.

They are won through pace.

Who sets the pace often sets the meaning.

Fast tempo favors:
	•	emotional reflex
	•	shallow confidence
	•	social pressure
	•	false binaries

Slow tempo favors:
	•	definition
	•	distinction
	•	evidence
	•	invariant selection

So one of the strongest tactics is simple:

Do not let someone else’s urgency become your ontology.

Just because they want instant closure does not mean reality has provided it.

⸻

8. The frame hierarchy

Not all frames are equal. Rank them.

Weak frame

Based on vibe, pressure, or implication.

Medium frame

Based on social norms or expectations.

Strong frame

Based on explicit definitions, evidence, and stable criteria.

Sovereign frame

Based on invariants that survive across contexts.

Example of a sovereign frame:

“Use standards that still hold when the emotional charge is gone.”

That is hard to beat because it generalizes.

⸻

9. The anti-capture doctrine

Here are the main traps.

Trap 1: Defending labels

Once you start arguing over whether you are “weak,” “crazy,” “late,” “afraid,” or “obsessed,” you may already be trapped.

Instead ask:
“Who defined that label, and by what standard?”

Trap 2: False urgency

Someone acts like a conclusion must be reached now.

Ask:
“What changes if we wait and assess more cleanly?”

Trap 3: Moral smuggling

A descriptive claim sneaks in a moral judgment.

Example:
“You hesitated” becomes “you’re unreliable.”

Separate observation from valuation.

Trap 4: Binary coercion

Two options are presented when there are five.

Ask:
“What possibilities are being excluded by this framing?”

